A small church on Carrer de Ferran in the Gothic Quarter. It is possible to enter the church from the same street
A small courtyard with Roman columns from the Temple of Augustus dating back to the 1st century BCE, an ideal visit for archaeology buffs
A small chapel in the lower part of the Gothic Quarter

place (used for folder name): Plaza de Josep Puig i Cadafalch

place (used for folder name): Santa Maria del Pi Bell Tower
place_desc: The Bell Tower of 'The Basilica of Santa Maria del Pi' can be accessed by a tour of the church. The church is situated in the heart of The Gothic Quarter and near to La Rambla
Currently, one of the two accessible towers inside Sagrada Familia, offering tours. The nativity tower is known locally as Torre del Naixement
Currently, one of the two accessible towers inside Sagrada Familia, offering tours. The passion tower is known locally as Torre de la Passió

A large park on the hillside near to the Bunkers of Carmel, in the neighbourhood of Horta-Guinardo
Spacious recreational mini-park, featuring a small pond water feature and playgrounds, with a cafe and a terrace

A busy and beautiful pedestrian avenue stretching four blocks north of La Sagrada Familia with views of the spectacular building itself. The rambla plays host to high street shops, restaurants and places to eat, bars and more
Barcelona is famous for its sheer number of escape rooms in the city. There are also escape rooms available in English, but check websites before booking

place (used for folder name): Plaza Espanya Centre Comercial Las Arenas
place_desc: A huge round multi-storey building next to Plaza Espanya housing hundred of shops, restaurants, a tremendous viewpoint and a cinema
A popular seafront promenade overlooking the Port Olimpic boating marina, surrounded by night clubs, bars, restaurants, hotels and the casino

place_remarks: Check the website for the latest performances and schedule
place_desc: A performing arts theatre situated near to Glories
The famous Moritz factory and brewery in the Sant Antoni neighbourhood of Barcelona. The bar is set on multiple floors and has a very large restaurant and a functioning brewery on site

The site of the former Damm factory and brewery in the Sagrada Familia neighbourhood of Barcelona. The factory has a permanent exhibition on site and plays host to tours and live events, such as concerts and festivals
An iconic pair of towers built in the 1920s, with a design inspired by Venice. The towers appear to stand at the doorway on the walk up to Palau Nacional from Plaza Espanya

A large open plaza and common meeting point for people visiting the area or passing through. Many key central tourist attractions are accessible from here, not to mention shops, bars and restaurants closeby

place (used for folder name): The View From The National Palace
place_desc: A grand view from the steps of Palau Nacional, towards Plaza Espanya and mount Tibidabo in the far distance
A viewpoint halfway up Montjuic out over the Mediterranean sea
A viewpoint, which offers magnificent views out over the sea and the Port of Barcelona, next to the Cable Car station on Montjuic. There is also a cafe next to it
A magnificent lookout point from high up near to the Castle of Montjuic in the wooded area, overlooking the Port of Barcelona and the sea

place_remarks: Check the official website for show times and booking options
place_desc: A historical landmark theatre showcasing operas, concerts and dance recitals with a spectacular interior

place_label: Centre de Cultura Contemporània de Barcelona (CCCB)
place_remarks: The centre is closed on Mondays. Free admission days exist. Check the website for more details.
place_desc: The Centre de Cultura Contemporània de Barcelona (CCCB) is an arts centre in Raval. The CCCB focusses on the showcasing of artefacts relating to Barcelona and its urban culture

Lloret de Mar is a town on the Costa Brava. It boasts several Mediterranean beaches, the medieval hillside 'Castle of Sant Joan' to the east and the Iglesia de Sant Romà, a church showcasing examples of both Catalan Gothic and modernist architecture

Tossa de Mar is situated in Catalonia, Spain, on the Costa Brava some 100 kilometres north of Barcelona and 100 kilometres south of the French border. Its closest airport is Girona Airport, a short distance to the north

place (used for folder name): The Castle at Tossa de Mar
place_desc: The Castle of Tossa de Mar is situated on a rocky outcrop, which juts out into the sea, just south of the Bay of Tossa. The Iconic 12th-century castle is popular with tourists and features fortification walls, numerous towers and a courtyard, not forgetting a collection of quaint bars and restaurants, supporting the foot-fall to the area all year round

The Old Town of Girona boasts over 2,000 years of history, which is reflected in its buildings. It has 2 fortified enclosures; one Roman and another from medieval times. Like Barcelona, it also has the old Jewish Quarter 'Call Jueu', a series of winding streets, Gothic buildings, Baroque monuments and Arab baths
The Church of Colònia Güell is an unfinished work by Antoni Gaudí and situated outside of Barcelona. Originally built as a place of worship for the people in the suburb of Santa Coloma de Cervelló

place (used for folder name): Temple of the Sacred Heart of Jesus
place_desc: The holy temple and church at the top of Mount Tibidabo, adorned by a large Christ statue and a huge bronze sacred heard statue. The church sits next to the entrance to the Tibidabo Theme Park

place_remarks: Check the website for the full programme of film screenings
place_desc: The Barcelona Open Air Cinema operates during the warmer summer months next to the Castle of Montjuic. Hundreds of film-goers sit together on the grass and watch a film under the stars

place_remarks: Occurs in January. Check the route map before you set off
place_desc: The Day of the Three Kings or Epiphany Day is a religious day of celebration. In Barcelona, there is an annual parade which travels slowly through the streets from Via Laietana to Plaza Espanya and the Magic Fountain

place_remarks: Occurs in February or March
place_desc: The calçotada is a gastronomic feast typically occurring in the western region of Catalonia. Calçots are a variety of onion/leek, specially cultivated for this purpose and are roasted directly on the flames and eaten by hand in combination with a special sauce

place_remarks: Occurs end of February or March

place_desc: An epic parade between Carrer de San Salvador and Gran de Gràcia
A week long flamenco festival that follows Easter

place_remarks: Occurs in May each year
place_desc: During the weekend of the Barcelona Formula One, the city more busy with octane revellers flocking to the circuit, which is situated some 30 minutes from Barcelona by train near to Granollers

place_remarks: Occurs in July each year
Occurs in July each year
place_desc: During the hot July summer month, the Valencian town of Benicassim plays host to this huge week long music festival, with hundred of acts

place_remarks: Occurs in February each year
place_desc: A 3 day festival of light and sound happening at various locations in the neighbourhood of Poblenou. Watch as tourists and locals flock to the area in the evening to marvel at the curious light installations and performances

place_remarks: Occurs end of June each year. Check the program for more information
place_desc: An annual Pride festival and march in Barcelona, occurring near to Plaza Espanya

place_remarks: Occurs in August each year
place_desc: One of, if not the biggest, reggae music festivals in Europe offering a full week of live reggae, dub, African and Caribbean music from heavy-hitting artists in the reggae scene. 2018 saw the 25th anniversary of the Rototom Festival

place_remarks: Occurs in August each year
place_desc: The annual festival of the neighbourhood of Sants, which hosts music, dance, arts and food stalls for a full week in the streets of the neighbourhood

A large plaza square in the Gracia neighbourhood frequented mainly by tourists and locallers looking to sit outside and enjoy one of the surrounding tapas restaurants, wine bars or coffee shops, which serve the plaza
This viewpoint is above Park Güell in Carmel Hill and it is situated at the highest part of the hill offering unparalleled views out over the city

place (used for folder name): Avenue of the Portal of the Angel
place_desc: A major shopping street running from Plaza Catalunya into the Gothic Quarter, featuring major highstreet brands

A bustling lively square next to The Cathedral. The plaza changes on a daily basis to accommodate local events, markets, processions, festivals and musical activities and is a very central, popular place for tourists

The 'Plaza de la Villa of Madrid' is a square in the Gothic Quarter just off the La Rambla. The square contains significant historical archaeological remains, after being exposed during an urban development project back in 1958. These archaeological finding were later preserved and exposed in situ, integrating them into the square's urban environment

One of the main highstreets in the Sant Pere, Santa Caterina I La Ribera neighbourhood, known also as El Born. This busy street houses many restaurants and bars as well as offering a key meeting place to tourists and locallers alike
The passeig of Joan of Borbo runs nearly north to south and connects Barceloneta metro station with Plaza de Mar and the beaches of Barceloneta

place_remarks: Most of the restaurants open from 7 but peak time can be as late as 10pm
place_desc: Carrer Ample in the 'bottom' of The Gothic Quarter has many nearly hidden but unique and homely tapas restaurants, distributed along the street, great for dinner or drinks opportunities
A small but vibrant plaza in the heart of El Born, housing a few local restaurants and regularly busy all day long, especially in the warmer summer months

place_label: Drinks @ Carrer de Joaquín Costa Raval
place (used for folder name): Drinks @ Carrer de Joaquin Costa Raval
place_desc: The street of Joaquin Costa in the Raval neighbourhood has many bars open late into the night and attracts, in the summer, a younger audience. Most bars and restaurants are small and give a true flavour of the regular Barcelona drinking culture, offering bars not so much frequented by tourists

place_label: Drinks @ Carrer del Parlament Sant Antoni
place (used for folder name): Drinks @ Carrer del Parlament Sant Antoni
place_desc: Parlament Street is a somewhat up and coming street in the Sant Antoni neighbourhood with an elegant and hip drinking culture, frequented by locallers and tourists alike

A large retail centre jutting out into the sea near to Barceloneta, housing restaurants, clothing outlets and electronics shops, near to the Barcelona Aquarium

A nice little square tucked away just inside El Born, mainly used by the surrounding restaurants and bars, with outdoor eating and drinking opportunities all year round
Nova Icaria beach plays host to volleyball nets and various meetups and groups gather here to play volleyball all year round

place_remarks: The plaza has a few food & drink options for visitors wishing to enjoy a coffee or glass of wine whilst watching the world go by
place_desc: The mini plaza is steeped in history and plays a crucial role in the whole medieval street vibe incorporating twisty winding streets all too recognisable of the typical Barcelona flair

place_remarks: Check opening times or arrange a guided tour
place_desc: One of many bomb shelters for the people of Barcelona during the Spanish civil war, offering guided tours

place_remarks: Occurs in or around July each year

A concrete skate and BMX park, frequented by boarders, skaters and BMX cyclists, situated near to the beach of Mar Bella. In the summer month, the skate park is thriving with activity late into the evening

place_remarks: The museum is closed on Mondays
place_desc: An art deco building housing Greek, Roman and prehistoric artifacts

place_remarks: It is possible to walk around the exterior castle walls and the perimeter of the castle, for free

A huge indoor arena, which was first used in the 1992 Olympics and now plays host to sporting events and concerts
A small park green space to the south west of La Sagrada Familia, offering a little respite from the tourists visiting the famous building
